// Parsing will be done by first collecting all the labels and storing their line numbers, then the script commands will be dealt with
// a line at a time.

// This contains a list of all the different combinations of commands and stuff that can possibly make up a valid
// line of script. When a line of script is parsed is breaks up each capitalised word (as defined as a series of characters
// without a SPACE in them) and then they are compared against each of these archetypes below. First the number of arguments
// will be taken into account to narrow down the search and then it'll check to see if all the arguments fall into the categories
// of the archetype. It'll probably be a fairly slow procedure, I reckon.

// Once each script is parsed, it's tokenised version will be added to a big list of script lines (with it's GOTOs all changed accordingly).

// There are a few special names used in the script archetypes which don't correspond to the below lists, these are:
// LABEL (this tells the parser to check through the list of goto labels for a match - causing an error if it can't find one)
// NUMBER (this tells the parser to check through the list of goto labels for a match - causing an error if it can't find one)
// Either of these.

// Once it finds a line that matches all the arguments given it gives a little whoop of joy and then stores the tokenised version in a
// temporary program array.

// By each of the "NAME" lists you'll notice there is a value. The value denotes the tag value of the command which the interpreter
// uses to identify the type of data. A value of -1 means it's not stored as it's just an ignored filler command.

// Note that where there are alternate arguments which make up a line, there should be no duplication of names in the differing
// lists as otherwise the first one will be selected. However this shouldn't occur unless some foolish mistakes are made. This is
// the achilles heel of this shortcut system, really, but with a bit of diligence it won't bite me in the arse.
// If it does become a problem, though I guess it'll mean I have to properly prototype each command type, although this won't be
// a *huge* problem. In fact it might well save a lot of hassle later on. Perhaps I'll add in a system whereby each word in the syntax
// list can have a specific instance attached, such as COMMAND:START meaning COMMAND tag_id and word START within that list only.

